      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Blimey, a mortgage statement from those fancy humans at Wells Fargo! What's happening is that, much like a scouting party of trash-eating goblins, the early payments go almost entirely to the *most immediate* threat: the interest. These early payments are like feeding the goblin horde; they mostly keep the interest-hungry loan spirits satisfied. You'll see a huge swing, though, because even the smallest line of goblins eventually start chipping away at the main pile of gold—your principal!\n\nTo put it simply, in the beginning, the interest portion of your 6.5% rate is massive, far outweighing the principal reduction. Imagine a single, very large, very hungry goblin—that's the interest, and it eats most of your first few payments! By year five, while you *are* paying down more principal than you did in the first six months, the bulk of the money is still mostly covering that interest bill. It's a slow, grinding process, which is just how most low-level goblin banditry works; they chip away bit by agonizing bit until the prize is theirs.\n\nBy contrast, in year 25, because a significant chunk of the loan balance",
