      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "No need to mind the pixies of pun! The reason this keeps happening is that interest is calculated on the *remaining* loan balance, which is massive at the start. For your 30-year, $300,000 mortgage at 6.5%, your fixed monthly payment is about $1,896. The mathematical grind is relentless, much like watching a whole warren of goblins slowly build a nuisance mound in your garden.\n\nHere’s the rough breakdown: In Year 5, your payment is still heavily weighted toward interest, maybe around 75-80% going to interest and only 20-25% to principal. At Year 25, however, the beast has been sufficiently thinned, and your ratio dramatically flips; you'll find that 50% or more of that $1,896 is now actively knocking down the principal balance! Seeing that shift is satisfying, even if the early years feel like you're just throwing scraps to a greedy, avaricious goblin boss.\n\n*Since I don't have your exact starting principal, these are approximations based on a standard $300k loan, but they illustrate",
